We are currently addressing an issue affecting a portion of the West US datacenter following an unexpected utility power interruption. Backup power systems remain active, and the facility has been fully operational since 12:30 UTC. Both power and physical network connectivity have been restored.

Most services in the region are operating normally. Some resources that depend on the previously impacted datacenter may continue to experience degraded availability as storage and compute components complete their recovery.

Our engineering and datacenter teams are actively validating the health of dependent systems and progressing recovery efforts.

We will provide the next update in 60 minutes or sooner if conditions change.

'''Troy''' is an abandoned town in [[Lafayette County, Florida|Lafayette County]], [[Florida]], [[United States]] that served as its county seat. Just like Fort Fanning, Fort "McKoon" (Macomb), Branford, Luraville and Wilcox, it was built as a boat landing on the Suwannee River about nine miles upriver from Branford.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=September 1940 |title=History of Lafayette County by Guy M. McClain |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123 |url-status= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=May 25, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory |pages= |at=Archived here: [https://archive.today/20240526063334/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=1/1], [https://archive.today/20240526063342/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=2/2], [https://archive.today/20240526004008/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3/3], [https://archive.today/20240526064320/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=4/4],[https://archive.today/20240526063413/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=5/5], [https://archive.today/20240526063433/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=6/6], [https://archive.today/20240526063444/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=7/7], [https://archive.today/20240526063449/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=8/8], [https://archive.today/20240526063502/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=9/9] at Archive Today, May 25, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Roberts |first=Robert B. |url=http://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhi0000robe |title=Encyclopedia of historic forts : the military, pioneer, and trading posts of the United States |date=1988 |publisher=New York : Macmillan ; London : Collier Macmillan |others=Internet Archive |isbn=978-0-02-926880-3 |page=184}}</ref> It was also known at times as Macintosh. According to one account, it was built between 1860 and 1862, so close to the water that the courthouse had to be moved a quarter of a mile because of flooding.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=September 1940 |title=History of Lafayette County by Guy M. McClain |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123?id=2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240525222657/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123?id=2 |archive-date=May 25, 2024 |access-date=May 25, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory |page=2}}</ref> A second account says its log courthouse was built in 1857.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=1939 |title=History of Lafayette County |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240526004008/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3 |archive-date=May 26, 2024 |access-date=May 26, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory}}</ref>
'''Troy''' is an abandoned town in [[Lafayette County, Florida|Lafayette County]], [[Florida]], United States that served as its county seat. Just like Fort Fanning, Fort "McKoon" (Macomb), Branford, Luraville and Wilcox, it was built as a boat landing on the Suwannee River about nine miles upriver from Branford.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=September 1940 |title=History of Lafayette County by Guy M. McClain |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123 |url-status= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=May 25, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory |pages= |at=Archived here: [https://archive.today/20240526063334/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=1/1], [https://archive.today/20240526063342/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=2/2], [https://archive.today/20240526004008/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3/3], [https://archive.today/20240526064320/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=4/4],[https://archive.today/20240526063413/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=5/5], [https://archive.today/20240526063433/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=6/6], [https://archive.today/20240526063444/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=7/7], [https://archive.today/20240526063449/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=8/8], [https://archive.today/20240526063502/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=9/9] at Archive Today, May 25, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Roberts |first=Robert B. |url=http://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofhi0000robe |title=Encyclopedia of historic forts : the military, pioneer, and trading posts of the United States |date=1988 |publisher=New York : Macmillan ; London : Collier Macmillan |others=Internet Archive |isbn=978-0-02-926880-3 |page=184}}</ref> It was also known at times as Macintosh. According to one account, it was built between 1860 and 1862, so close to the water that the courthouse had to be moved a quarter of a mile because of flooding.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=September 1940 |title=History of Lafayette County by Guy M. McClain |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123?id=2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240525222657/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321123?id=2 |archive-date=May 25, 2024 |access-date=May 25, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory |page=2}}</ref> A second account says its log courthouse was built in 1857.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Works Progress Administration |first=Historical Records Survey |date=1939 |title=History of Lafayette County |url=https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240526004008/https://www.floridamemory.com/items/show/321122?id=3 |archive-date=May 26, 2024 |access-date=May 26, 2024 |website=State Archives of Florida, Florida Memory}}</ref>


Most of the town was burned in the chaos following the end of the Civil War. The first account says that the county records were lost, but the second contradicts this, saying that the local tax assessor and clerk of the circuit court hid them at his home.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> A third account agrees that the county records were saved by being hidden in a corn crib.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mikell |first=Ira |date=2006-01-19 |title=Local resident remembers Old Troy and New Troy |url=https://www.valdostadailytimes.com/mayo/local-resident-remembers-old-troy-and-new-troy/article_41f4302a-1d80-5503-9b8b-aa7535ea20cc.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240526033201/https://www.valdostadailytimes.com/mayo/local-resident-remembers-old-troy-and-new-troy/article_41f4302a-1d80-5503-9b8b-aa7535ea20cc.html |archive-date=May 26, 2024 |access-date=2024-05-26 |website=Valdosta Daily Times |language=en}}</ref> The town was rebuilt a quarter of a mile away, named New Troy, and remained the county seat until the courthouse burned again and county governance was moved to Mayo in 1893.

The '''Serie B Profesional''' (usually called simply '''Serie B''') was the second division of Chilean [[football (soccer)]] in 1935 until 1942.<ref>[https://asifuch.cl/los-117-clubes-profesionales-del-futbol-chileno/ Los 117 clubes profesionales del fútbol chileno]</ref> The tournament was played on a home-and-away round-robin basis. It was created by the [[Asociación de Fútbol de Santiago]] (AFS), affiliated with the [[Football Federation of Chile|Chilean Football Federation]], and at that time it corresponded to the lower of the two professional divisions of Chilean football. The most successful team was [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]], which won the tournament on two occasions.
The '''Serie B Profesional''' (usually called simply '''Serie B''') was the second division of Chilean [[football (soccer)]] in 1935 until 1942.<ref>[https://asifuch.cl/los-117-clubes-profesionales-del-futbol-chileno/ Los 117 clubes profesionales del fútbol chileno]</ref> The tournament was played on a home-and-away round-robin basis. It was established by the [[Asociación de Fútbol de Santiago]] (AFS), affiliated with the [[Football Federation of Chile|Chilean Football Federation]], and at that time it corresponded to the lower of the two professional divisions of Chilean football. The most successful team was [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]], which won the tournament on two occasions.

On April 19, 1927, following a mandate from the Chilean Football Federation, it merged with the [[Liga Metropolitana de Deportes]], the [[Liga Santiago de Football]], and the [[Liga Nacional Obrera de Football]], adopting the name Liga Central de Football de Santiago (LCF). In 1930, it returned to its original designation.

I have always felt that it is essential to have rich, enjoyable articles to read, since the goal is to keep readers engaged and to spark their curiosity.
